  "prompt": "Why does the sun rise in the east and set in the west but not the north and south?",
  "response": "The sun appears to rise in the east and set in the west due to the rotation of the Earth. Earth rotates on its axis from west to east, which makes celestial bodies like the sun, moon, and stars appear to move across the sky from east to west.\n\nHere's a breakdown of why this happens:\n\n1. **Rotation Direction**: Earth rotates counterclockwise (as viewed from above the North Pole), which means the eastern part of the planet moves toward the sun first, and the western part of the planet moves into the sunlight afterward. This creates the illusion of the sun rising in the east and setting in the west.\n\n2. **Observer's Perspective**: From any given point on Earth's surface, the horizon obscures your view in all directions. As the Earth rotates, the sun appears over the eastern horizon first, travels across the sky, and then disappears below the western horizon.\n\n3. **Earth's Axial Tilt**: Earth's axis is tilted relative to its orbit around the sun, which causes variations in daylight and seasonal differences but doesn't change the basic east-to-west path of the sun across the sky from the perspective of most places on Earth. \n\nThe paths that the sun follows do vary somewhat across the year due to the axial tilt. During solstices and equinoxes, the sun's path shifts slightly northward or southward, but it consistently rises roughly in the east and sets roughly in the west.",
